<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-10-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-10-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="316" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Brun</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-10-25"><hi rend="italic">October 25,
                                1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 351.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor, in reply, to your note
                            of the 19th instant, to inform you that I have to-day instructed the
                            minister of the United States to Salvador to afford his protection to
                            Danish subjects and interests in the Republic named.</p>
                        <p>Mr. Merry’s protection will consist of the exercise of his good offices
                            with the assent of the Government of Salvador, and will, of course,
                            involve no assumption of representative functions on behalf of the
                            Government of Denmark.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>